@variant-of equity/shared-maintenance
@paper-source /home/joe/npt/paper-v2.3/paper_v2.3.html
@divergence The canonical pattern deepens this via whole-board play
(backward propagation as the difference between a system that learns
and a system that merely runs) and Sen (capability development
through use).  The paper frames it as a commons governance problem —
materials age, local rework is invisible, and a light-touch review
cycle with attribution-as-author is the missing norm.  The paper
explicitly cites Ostrom's "rules matched to local conditions" and
treats this as a developing knowledge commons.  This variant records
the paper's framing.

! conclusion: Trainers praise the materials as a gold standard but content ages, requires local adaptation, and cannot easily be upstreamed.  The result is ad hoc rework as invisible labour.  The missing norm is a coordination rule: every adaptation used more than once is shared, with the adapter credited as author, and a light-touch review cycle makes distributed stewardship the norm rather than the exception.
  + context: This is NPT Collective Action — specifically 3.2 Relational Integration and 3.4 Contextual Integration.  It is an intervention-tier pattern with medium coordination, but the coordination takes the form of a community norm rather than an organisational decision — a developing knowledge commons that requires distributed stewardship across a contributor community.  Where materials are reworked locally without upstreaming, the pattern's absence is the defining signature of absorbed input mode.
  + IF:
    A programme distributes high-quality training materials that trainers use and praise.  Trainers encounter materials that age, that need adaptation to local settings, and that could be improved by the rework each trainer does privately.  Contributing back to the shared resource would improve it for future trainers and reduce aggregate maintenance work.
  + HOWEVER:
    No upstream channel exists.  Each trainer reworks materials independently; adaptations stay local; the "gold standard" reputation erodes as content drifts from practice.  Maintenance falls to whoever notices a problem — ad hoc, unrecognised, on top of already constrained time.  Workload and capacity concerns are the most prevalent theme in the corpus (34 of 134 turns, 25%).  COM-B "policies, procedures, and resource allocation are appropriate" M=3.78 (below midpoint — the only pattern-relevant COM-B item to score below 4).  Trainers: T1 calls the Carpentries lessons a "gold standard"; T1: "every time I've done it, I haven't given enough time"; FG1.9 praises the materials.  Open licensing was planned but the stewardship infrastructure was not built.
  + THEN:
    The programme establishes a coordination rule: every adaptation used more than once is shared, with the adapter credited as author.  A light-touch review cycle makes distributed stewardship the community norm.  The contribution pathway is no harder to use than the consumption pathway.  This is the commons governance move — Ostrom's "rules matched to local conditions" applied to a developing knowledge commons.
  + BECAUSE:
    NPT Collective Action: 3.2 Relational Integration is the work of maintaining trust and cooperation between actors whose efforts the practice depends on; 3.4 Contextual Integration is the fit between the practice and its institutional-organisational context.  Invisible rework breaks both — the trainer carries unreciprocated maintenance labour, and the materials drift from the practice they were meant to support.

    Community-norm framing: Unlike Patterns 1 and 2, this pattern cannot be resolved by an organisational decision.  A central scaffold or a declared profile can be issued top-down; a stewardship norm cannot.  Coordination takes the form of a community rule of shared authorship, which the programme can seed but the community must sustain.  This is what the paper means by "distributed stewardship."

    Commons framing (Ostrom 1990): A knowledge commons requires rules matched to local conditions.  "Every adaptation used more than once is shared, credited as author" is one such rule — lightweight, low-cost, and aligned with how trainers already create value.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Establish open licensing with an active upstream channel (not licensing alone)
    - Adopt the coordination rule: every adaptation used more than once is shared, adapter credited as author
    - Implement a light-touch review cycle with named reviewers
    - Make contributing as frictionless as consuming (the friction gradient should favour upstream flow)
    - Surface the aggregate labour: count contributions, count reviews, show the commons at work
    - Test: can a local adaptation reach the shared repository within one cycle?
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Local adaptations can flow back into the shared materials through a defined light-touch review cycle.  Adapters are credited as authors.  The upstream pathway is no harder than the downstream consumption pathway.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - No upstream channel: local learning never propagates; the commons degrades
    - Licensing without stewardship: open licence exists but no one curates or reviews
    - Invisible rework: maintenance is unrecognised work that compounds overload
    - Ad hoc sharing: "a couple of colleagues have uploaded their slides" — unsystematic
    - Drifting gold standard: reputation maintained while practice diverges
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Paper v2.3, Pattern 3: Shared Maintenance
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("a gold standard of how to run an intro to reproducible research session")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("every time I've done it, I haven't given enough time")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("a couple of colleagues have uploaded their slides")
    - Corpus theme: workload/capacity, 34 of 134 turns (25%), most prevalent
    - COM-B: "policies, procedures, and resource allocation are appropriate" M=3.78
    - Ostrom (1990) — "rules matched to local conditions"
    - REDF proposal: permissive licensing was planned; stewardship infrastructure was not
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Collective Action 3.2 Relational Integration and 3.4 Contextual Integration as stated in the companion journal article.
    Tier: Intervention.  Coordination: Medium, but community-norm rather than organisational-decision.
    Implementation-mode link: unshared rework is the defining signature of absorbed input.
    The paper names a specific coordination rule (every adaptation used more than once is shared, credited as author) and cites Ostrom 1990 directly.
